:::summary
Hannibal Barca (247–183 BC) was the Carthaginian general widely regarded as one of the greatest military commanders in all of history. His audacious crossing of the Alps with war elephants and his devastating victories over Roman armies — especially at Cannae (216 BC) — made him Rome's most terrifying enemy and shaped Roman military thinking for centuries.
:::

